  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Joseph Priestley's range of intellectual interests was very great, even by the standards of the eighteenth century.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "He argued the case for materialism perhaps more cogently than did any British thinker before recent times.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "He presented determinism vigorously, with a focus on the central issue of the nature of causation.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "He defended scientific realism against Thomas Reid's Common Sense realism and against (as he saw it) David Hume's phenomenonalism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "He articulated, against Hume, a working scientist's account of causation, induction and scientific progress.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "He defended the Argument from Design against Hume's penetrating criticisms.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "His attempt to combine theism, materialism and determinism is audacious and original.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "He tried to show that such a system does not lapse into pantheism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "As a political thinker, he distinguished usefully between civil and political liberty, and argued the case for extensive civil liberties.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "His liberalism is closely bound up with his account of historical progress.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "He was perhaps the most thorough British exponent of a Providentialist account of progress.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "His ultimate aim was to combine Enlightenment principles with a modernized Christian theism.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Priestley's materialism rests on three main arguments, each of which bears interesting scientific connections.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Priestley's determinism can be more briefly described, as it rests on one main argument, forcefully expounded in his Doctrine of Philosophical Necessity of 1777.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Priestley's general position, then, is that naturalism fails to make sense of biology.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Since both these moves fail, we are forced to postulate an intelligent Creator, following the analogy of human creativity.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Priestley's life was one of perpetual disputation.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "He always regarded controversy as a service to truth, and it was his custom to answer every objection his critics could propose.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "When his arguments led him to seemingly paradoxical conclusions, he held to the arguments rather than reject the premises from which he started.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
